WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:28.820
Chapter 2 of Meditations of Marcus Aurelius 1. Begin the morning by saying to thyself,

00:28.820 --> 00:35.380
I shall meet with the busy body, the ungrateful, arrogant, deceitful, envious, unsocial.

00:36.100 --> 00:40.120
All these things happen to them by reason of their ignorance of what is good and evil.

00:40.760 --> 00:45.800
But I who have seen the nature of the good that is beautiful, and of the bad that it is ugly,

00:46.240 --> 00:51.980
and the nature of him who does wrong, that it is akin to me, not only of the same blood or seed,

00:52.320 --> 00:56.740
but that it participates in the same intelligence and the same portion of the divinity,

00:56.740 --> 01:01.700
I can neither be injured by any of them, for no one can fix on me what is ugly,

01:02.160 --> 01:05.360
nor can I be angry with my kinsman, nor hate him.

01:06.020 --> 01:13.480
For we are made for cooperation, like feet, like hands, like eyelids, like the rows of the upper and lower teeth.

01:13.880 --> 01:20.600
To act against one another then is contrary to nature, and it is acting against one another to be vexed and to turn away.

01:22.300 --> 01:28.160
2. Whatever this is that I am, it is a little flesh and breath, and the ruling part.

01:28.800 --> 01:32.900
Throw away thy books, no longer distract thyself, it is not allowed.

01:33.420 --> 01:38.740
But as if thou wast now dying, despise the flesh, it is blood and bones and a network,

01:39.440 --> 01:41.780
a conjecture of nerves, veins and arteries.

01:42.640 --> 01:47.260
See the breath also, what kind of a thing it is, air and not always the same,

01:47.580 --> 01:50.140
but every moment sent out and again sucked in.

01:50.700 --> 01:55.760
The third then is the ruling part. Consider thus, thou art an old man,

01:56.120 --> 02:01.820
no longer let this be a slave, no longer be pulled by the strings like a puppet to unsocial movements,

02:02.300 --> 02:06.660
no longer be either dissatisfied with thy present lot or shrink from the future.

02:07.780 --> 02:11.220
3. All that is from the gods is full of providence.

02:11.820 --> 02:19.420
That which is from fortune is not separated from nature or without an interweaving and involution with the things which are ordered by providence.

02:20.000 --> 02:23.820
From thence all things flow, and there is besides necessity,

02:24.300 --> 02:28.120
and that which is for the advantage of the whole universe, of which thou art a part.

02:28.720 --> 02:34.520
But that is good for every part of nature which the nature of the whole brings, and what serves to maintain this nature.

02:35.280 --> 02:38.600
Now the universe is preserved, as by the changes of the elements,

02:39.020 --> 02:41.660
so by the changes of things compounded of the elements.

02:42.280 --> 02:46.240
Let these principles be enough for thee, let them always be fixed opinions,

02:46.240 --> 02:50.660
but cast away the thirst after books, that thou mayest not die murmuring,

02:50.920 --> 02:54.880
but cheerfully, truly, and from thy heart thankful to the gods.

02:56.180 --> 02:59.960
4. Remember how long thou hast been putting off these things,

03:00.120 --> 03:05.340
and how often thou hast received an opportunity from the gods, and yet dost not use it.

03:05.900 --> 03:09.280
Thou must now at last perceive of what universe thou art a part,

03:09.720 --> 03:13.000
and of what administrator of the universe thy existence is in a flux,

03:13.480 --> 03:15.940
and that a limit of time is fixed for thee,

03:16.240 --> 03:19.820
which if thou dost not use for clearing away the clouds from thy mind,

03:20.260 --> 03:23.220
it will go, and thou wilt go, and it will never return.

03:24.840 --> 03:30.240
5. Every moment think steadily as a Roman, and a man to do what thou hast in hand,

03:30.400 --> 03:35.860
with perfect and simple dignity, and feeling of affection, and freedom, and justice,

03:36.460 --> 03:39.040
and to give thyself relief from all other thoughts.

03:39.040 --> 03:45.120
6. And thou wilt give thyself relief, if thou doest every act of thy life as if it were the last,

03:45.500 --> 03:49.900
laying aside all carelessness and passionate aversion from the commands of reason,

03:50.220 --> 03:55.720
and all hypocrisy, and self-love, and discontent with the portion which has been given to thee.

03:56.440 --> 04:00.580
7. Thou seest how few the things are, though which if a man lays hold of,

04:00.720 --> 04:05.280
he is able to live a life which flows in quiet, and is like the existence of the gods.

04:05.280 --> 04:10.560
For the gods in their part will require nothing more from him who observes these things.

04:11.900 --> 04:16.120
6. Do wrong to thyself, do wrong to thyself, my soul,

04:16.600 --> 04:19.540
but thou wilt no longer have the opportunity of honoring thyself.

04:20.780 --> 04:24.300
Every man's life is sufficient, but thine is nearly finished,

04:24.680 --> 04:30.120
though thy soul reverences not itself, but places thy felicity in the souls of others.

04:31.440 --> 04:35.400
7. Do the things external which fall upon thee distract thee?

04:35.980 --> 04:40.060
Give thyself time to learn something new and good, and cease to be whirled about.

04:40.680 --> 04:43.860
But then thou must also avoid being carried about the other way,

04:44.180 --> 04:47.980
for those too are triflers who have wearied themselves in life by their activity,

04:48.520 --> 04:53.500
and yet have no object to which to direct every movement, and in a word, all their thoughts.

04:54.900 --> 04:58.420
8. Through not observing what is in the mind of another man

04:58.420 --> 05:00.580
has seldom been seen to be unhappy.

05:01.320 --> 05:06.140
But those who do not observe the movements of their own minds must of necessity be unhappy.

05:07.620 --> 05:13.440
9. This thou must always bear in mind, what is the nature of the whole, and what is my nature,

05:13.880 --> 05:18.740
and how this is related to that, and what kind of a part it is of what kind of a whole,

05:19.440 --> 05:23.460
and that there is no one who hinders thee from always doing and saying the things

05:23.460 --> 05:26.580
which are according to the nature of which thou art a part.

05:27.720 --> 05:31.760
10. Theophrastus, in his comparison of bad acts,

05:32.160 --> 05:35.820
such a comparison as one would make in accordance with the common notions of mankind,

05:36.680 --> 05:40.880
says, like a true philosopher, that the offences which are committed through desire

05:40.880 --> 05:44.020
are more blamable than those which are committed through anger.

05:44.580 --> 05:47.980
For he who is excited by anger seems to turn away from reason

05:47.980 --> 05:50.620
with a certain pain and unconscious contraction.

05:51.220 --> 05:54.940
But he who offends through desire, being overpowered by pleasure,

05:54.940 --> 05:59.320
seems to be in a manner more intemperate and more womanish in his offences.

06:00.160 --> 06:04.060
Rightly then, and in a way worthy of philosophy, he said that the offence

06:04.060 --> 06:08.460
which is committed with pleasure is more blamable than that which is committed with pain.

06:08.960 --> 06:13.040
And on the whole the one is more like a person who has been first wronged

06:13.040 --> 06:15.040
and through pain is compelled to be angry.

06:15.520 --> 06:18.300
But the other is moved by his own impulse to do wrong,

06:18.580 --> 06:21.140
being carried toward doing something by desire.

06:22.920 --> 06:27.680
11. Since it is possible that thou mayest depart from life this very moment,

06:28.220 --> 06:30.460
regulate every act and thought accordingly.

06:31.160 --> 06:35.860
But to go away from among men, if there are gods, is not a thing to be afraid of,

06:36.120 --> 06:38.220
for the gods will not involve thee in evil.

06:38.760 --> 06:43.300
But if indeed they do not exist, or if they have no concern about human affairs,

06:43.800 --> 06:48.160
what is it to me to live in a universe devoid of gods or devoid of providence?

06:48.160 --> 06:52.680
But in truth they do exist, and they do not care for human things,

06:52.960 --> 06:57.700
and they have put all the means in man's power to enable him not to fall into real evils.

06:58.360 --> 07:02.860
And as to the rest, if there was anything evil, they would have provided for this also,

07:03.140 --> 07:07.060
that it should be altogether in a man's power not to fall into it.

07:07.780 --> 07:12.000
Now, that which does not make a man worse, how can it make a man's life worse?

07:12.440 --> 07:15.000
But neither through ignorance, nor having the knowledge,

07:15.000 --> 07:17.980
but not the power to guard against or correct these things,

07:18.120 --> 07:21.320
it is possible that the nature of the universe has overlooked them.

07:21.960 --> 07:24.680
Nor is it possible that it has made so great a mistake,

07:24.940 --> 07:27.260
either through want of power or want of skill,

07:27.620 --> 07:31.320
that good and evil should happen indiscriminately to the good and the bad.

07:32.100 --> 07:36.320
But death certainly, and life, honor and dishonor, pain and pleasure,

07:36.640 --> 07:39.720
all these things equally happen to good men and bad,

07:40.080 --> 07:42.800
being things which make us neither better nor worse.

07:42.800 --> 07:45.840
Therefore, they are neither good nor evil.

07:46.700 --> 07:49.720
Twelve. How quickly all these things disappear,

07:50.080 --> 07:54.420
in the universe the bodies themselves, but in time the remembrance of them.

07:55.180 --> 07:57.100
What is the nature of all sensible things,

07:57.340 --> 08:00.300
and particularly those which attract with the bait of pleasure,

08:00.700 --> 08:04.520
or terrify by pain, or are noised about by vapoury fame?

08:05.300 --> 08:10.460
How worthless and contemptible and sordid and perishable and dead they are.

08:10.980 --> 08:14.360
All this it is the part of the intellectual faculty to observe.

08:15.240 --> 08:19.220
To observe, too, who these are whose opinions and voices give reputation.

08:19.960 --> 08:23.940
What death is, and the fact that, if a man looks at it in himself,

08:24.240 --> 08:27.880
and by the abstract of power reflection, resolves into their parts

08:27.880 --> 08:31.100
all the things which present themselves to the imagination in it,

08:31.300 --> 08:34.860
he will then consider it to be nothing else than an operation of nature.

08:35.460 --> 08:39.080
And if anyone is afraid of an operation of nature, he is a child.

08:39.780 --> 08:42.620
This, however, is not only an operation of nature,

08:43.000 --> 08:46.320
but it is also a thing which conduces to the purposes of nature.

08:47.020 --> 08:49.720
To observe, too, how man comes near to the deity,

08:50.140 --> 08:54.020
and by what part of him, and when this part of man, is so disposed.

08:55.900 --> 09:00.920
Thirteen. Nothing is more wretched than a man who traverses everything in a round,

09:01.360 --> 09:04.500
and prides into things beneath the earth, as the poet says,

09:04.860 --> 09:08.180
and seeks by conjecture what is in the minds of his neighbours,

09:09.080 --> 09:12.440
perceiving that it is sufficient to attend to the demon within him,

09:12.700 --> 09:14.260
and to reverence it sincerely.

09:15.140 --> 09:18.720
And reverence of the demon consists in keeping it pure from passion,

09:19.160 --> 09:23.360
and thoughtlessness, and dissatisfaction with what comes from gods and men.

09:24.140 --> 09:27.200
For the things from gods merit veneration for their excellence,

09:27.780 --> 09:31.280
and the things from men should be dear to us by reason of kinship,

09:31.580 --> 09:37.040
and sometimes even in a manner they move our pity by reason of men's ignorance of good and bad.

09:37.040 --> 09:41.420
This defect being not less than that which deprives us of the power

09:41.420 --> 09:44.420
of distinguishing things that are white and black.

09:46.120 --> 09:49.760
Fourteen. Though thou shouldest be going to live three thousand years,

09:49.880 --> 09:52.020
and as many times ten thousand years,

09:52.340 --> 09:56.560
still remember that no man loses any other life than this which he now lives,

09:56.980 --> 09:59.820
nor lives any other than this which he now loses.

10:00.500 --> 10:03.280
The longest and shortest are thus brought to the same,

10:03.640 --> 10:05.460
for the present is the same to all,

10:05.460 --> 10:08.120
though that which perishes is not the same.

10:08.560 --> 10:11.360
And so that which is lost appears to be a mere moment.

10:12.140 --> 10:14.960
For a man cannot lose either the past or the future.

10:15.320 --> 10:18.380
For what a man has not, how can anyone take this from him?

10:19.080 --> 10:21.360
These two things then thou must bear in mind.

10:21.580 --> 10:25.080
The one, that all things from eternity are of like forms,

10:25.240 --> 10:28.000
and come round in a circle, and that it makes no difference

10:28.000 --> 10:31.300
whether a man shall see the same things during a hundred years,

10:31.540 --> 10:33.740
or two hundred, or an infinite time.

10:33.740 --> 10:38.560
And the second, that the longest-liver and he who will die soonest

10:38.560 --> 10:40.040
lose just the same.

10:40.680 --> 10:44.020
For the present is the only thing of which a man can be deprived,

10:44.520 --> 10:47.420
if it is true that this is the only thing which he has,

10:47.660 --> 10:50.440
and that a man cannot lose a thing if he has it not.

10:52.000 --> 10:54.460
Fifteen. Remember that all is opinion.

10:54.960 --> 10:57.600
For what was said by the Cynic Monomus is manifest,

10:58.160 --> 11:00.620
and manifest, too, is the use of what was said,

11:00.620 --> 11:04.660
if a man receives what may be gut out of it as far as it is true.

11:06.280 --> 11:09.160
Sixteen. The soul of man does violence to itself,

11:09.640 --> 11:13.020
first of all when it becomes as abscess, and, as it were,

11:13.200 --> 11:15.740
a tumor on the universe, so far as it can.

11:16.240 --> 11:20.380
For to be vexed at anything which happens is a separation of ourselves from nature,

11:20.920 --> 11:24.040
in some part of which the natures of all other things are contained.

11:24.960 --> 11:29.520
In the next place the soul does violence to itself when it turns away from any man,

11:29.520 --> 11:32.680
or even moves towards him with the intention of injuring,

11:32.920 --> 11:35.160
such as of the souls of those who are angry.

11:35.720 --> 11:38.540
In the third place the soul does violence to itself

11:38.540 --> 11:42.280
when it is overpowered by pleasure or by pain.

11:43.140 --> 11:47.760
Fourthly, when it plays a part and does or says anything insincerely and untruly.

11:48.880 --> 11:53.660
Fifthly, when it allows any act of its own and any movement to be without an aim,

11:54.140 --> 11:57.820
and does anything thoughtlessly and without considering what it is,

11:57.820 --> 12:01.720
being right that even the smallest things be done with reference to an end.

12:02.560 --> 12:08.260
And the end of rational animals is to follow the reason and the law of the most ancient city and polity.

12:10.020 --> 12:15.220
Seventeen. Of human life the time is a point, and the substance is in a flux,

12:15.740 --> 12:20.020
and the perception dull, and the composition of the whole body subject to putrefaction,

12:20.980 --> 12:26.520
and the soul of a whirl, and fortune hard to divine, and fame a thing devoid of judgment.

12:26.520 --> 12:31.840
And to say all in a word, everything which belongs to the body is a stream,

12:32.360 --> 12:35.320
and what belongs to the soul is a dream and vapor,

12:36.000 --> 12:41.720
and life is a warfare and a stranger's sojourn, and after fame is oblivion.

12:42.600 --> 12:48.200
What then is that which is able to conduct a man? One thing and only one, philosophy.

12:48.860 --> 12:53.480
But this consists in keeping the demon within a man free from violence and unharmed,

12:53.480 --> 12:59.580
superior to pains and pleasures, doing nothing without a purpose, nor yet falsely and with hypocrisy,

13:00.480 --> 13:04.040
not feeling the need of another man's doing or not doing anything.

13:04.640 --> 13:08.100
And besides, accepting all that happens and all that is allotted,

13:08.440 --> 13:12.300
as coming from thence, wherever it is, from whence he himself came.

13:12.900 --> 13:16.000
And finally, waiting for death with a cheerful mind,

13:16.320 --> 13:21.360
as being nothing else than a dissolution of the elements of which every living being is compounded.

13:21.360 --> 13:26.700
But, if there is no harm to the elements themselves in each continually changing into another,

13:27.120 --> 13:31.540
why should a man have any apprehension about the change and dissolution of all the elements?

13:32.180 --> 13:36.480
For it is according to nature, and nothing is evil which is according to nature.

13:38.880 --> 13:39.920
This incarnuntum.

13:42.240 --> 13:43.940
End of chapter 2

